WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.176 --> 00:00:08.050
JILLIAN: Linden Schaffer
is a wellness travel

00:00:08.050 --> 00:00:09.460
expert and consultant.

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:12.760
Early on in her fashion career,
she realized the way she worked

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:15.160
was turning her into a
tightly wound ball of stress

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:18.680
and tension, which I'm sure
many of us can relate to.

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:20.500
So before every
business trip, she

00:00:20.500 --> 00:00:23.680
conducted hours of research
planning her own self-care

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:26.230
in her few precious
hours of downtime.

00:00:26.230 --> 00:00:27.910
And it changed her life.

00:00:27.910 --> 00:00:30.850
Today, Linden leads
travelers around the world

00:00:30.850 --> 00:00:34.360
on wellness vacations via
Pravassa, the first wellness

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:35.610
travel company.

00:00:35.610 --> 00:00:38.290
Linden has been recognized
as a leader in her field

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:40.820
and as a winner of the
prestigious British Airways

00:00:40.820 --> 00:00:43.150
Face of Opportunity contest.

00:00:43.150 --> 00:00:45.670
She contributes to columns
in the "Huffington Post"

00:00:45.670 --> 00:00:48.670
and "mindbodygreen," where she
writes about wellness, travel,

00:00:48.670 --> 00:00:49.840
and lifestyle.

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:51.920
She is a regular
speaker at conferences,

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:54.580
including the "New York
Times" and "Los Angeles Times"

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:55.750
travel shows.

00:00:55.750 --> 00:00:58.780
Her first book, "Living Well on
the Road, Health and Wellness

00:00:58.780 --> 00:01:01.540
for Every Traveler," became
a number one best seller

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:02.830
upon release.

00:01:02.830 --> 00:01:05.434
And here's Linden.

00:01:05.434 --> 00:01:08.920
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:12.267 --> 00:01:13.600
LINDEN SCHAFFER: Good afternoon.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:15.810
Thank you, Jillian, so
much for hosting me.

00:01:15.810 --> 00:01:16.660
Thanks to Google.

00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:19.900
Thank you guys for spending
your lunch time with me.

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:23.130
I'm really excited to be
here today and talk to you

00:01:23.130 --> 00:01:26.310
about living well on the
road, or what I also call,

00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:29.250
how to plan a business trip
that doesn't kill you--

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:32.130
very important in the day
and age that we work in.

00:01:32.130 --> 00:01:33.330
So who am I?

00:01:33.330 --> 00:01:36.990
And why am I here to talk
to you about this today?

00:01:36.990 --> 00:01:39.060
I am the girl who,
at 16 years old,

00:01:39.060 --> 00:01:41.527
had my first international
travel experience.

00:01:41.527 --> 00:01:43.110
And it's something
that stuck with me.

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:45.060
I was able to go to Australia.

00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:47.400
And ever since
then, my wanderlust

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:50.010
and my idea of wanting
to explore the world

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:52.710
was deeply seeded
and rooted in me.

00:01:52.710 --> 00:01:57.270
I spent 15 years in the fashion
industry in New York City.

00:01:57.270 --> 00:01:59.802
And my time there, I would
go in for my job interviews.

00:01:59.802 --> 00:02:01.260
And we'd have this
great interview.

00:02:01.260 --> 00:02:03.450
We'd talk about what
I was doing or about

00:02:03.450 --> 00:02:04.770
to do with this company.

00:02:04.770 --> 00:02:06.870
And at the end, the
interviewer would say, hey,

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:07.953
do you have any questions?

00:02:07.953 --> 00:02:09.210
And I would say yes.

00:02:09.210 --> 00:02:13.200
How much is this a
work travel situation?

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:15.570
And how much vacation
time do I get?

00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:17.890
So you can imagine, these
interviewers were like,

00:02:17.890 --> 00:02:19.170
wait a second.

00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:21.600
Your biggest concern
about this job

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:23.880
is how much time you get
to spend out of the office?

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:26.770
OK, let's think about
this a little bit.

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:28.992
So luckily enough,
throughout the career

00:02:28.992 --> 00:02:30.450
that I had in the
fashion industry,

00:02:30.450 --> 00:02:31.860
I was able to travel a lot.

00:02:31.860 --> 00:02:33.529
I would travel domestically.

00:02:33.529 --> 00:02:34.820
I would travel internationally.

00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:38.040
I would travel for weeks on
end with no break in between.

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:39.960
And there I was one
morning, waking up

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:44.160
in a hotel room in Italy and
having no idea where I was.

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:45.960
So I'm sure that's
happened to some of you

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:47.310
in this room before.

00:02:47.310 --> 00:02:49.144
You had no idea
between the jet lag,

00:02:49.144 --> 00:02:51.060
between where you were
yesterday, where you're

00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:53.347
going tomorrow, where are you?

00:02:53.347 --> 00:02:54.430
And I said, you know what?

00:02:54.430 --> 00:02:56.187
I got to-- something
here has got to give.

00:02:56.187 --> 00:02:57.270
Something's got to change.

00:02:57.270 --> 00:02:58.470
I can't be stressed out.

00:02:58.470 --> 00:02:59.460
I can't be burnt out.

00:02:59.460 --> 00:03:01.900
I can't be productive
in this situation.

00:03:01.900 --> 00:03:04.230
So what is it that I can do
to change the way that I'm

00:03:04.230 --> 00:03:06.580
living while I travel?

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:10.830
So what I did was I started
to just simply pool from tools

00:03:10.830 --> 00:03:12.640
that I had used in my own life.

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:15.390
So whether it was yoga
practicing or meditation

00:03:15.390 --> 00:03:17.580
or eating healthy
at home, I figured

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:20.250
there's got to be a way
that I can implement this

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:22.210
while I'm on the road as well.

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:24.990
So I started doing my own
little tips and tricks.

00:03:24.990 --> 00:03:27.259
And I would take
that circuit again.

00:03:27.259 --> 00:03:29.800
I would see the same people that
I was always traveling with.

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:30.640
And they would look at me.

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:32.430
And they would say,
you know what, Linden?

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:33.600
You seem rested.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:34.440
You seem happy.

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:35.730
You seem healthy.

00:03:35.730 --> 00:03:37.230
What has changed?

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:39.380
And how do I get that?

00:03:39.380 --> 00:03:41.130
So I started to think
to myself, OK, there

00:03:41.130 --> 00:03:42.180
must be something here.

00:03:42.180 --> 00:03:45.550
Everybody is stressed out,
burnt out, living on the road

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:46.800
when they travel for business.

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:49.110
And they need to get
some sanity back.

00:03:49.110 --> 00:03:51.810
They need to get some
semblance of themselves back.

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:56.070
And this led organically
to the launch of Pravassa,

00:03:56.070 --> 00:03:58.140
which is the wellness
travel company I run.

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:00.090
It was the first wellness
travel company that

00:04:00.090 --> 00:04:02.010
was created here in the US.

00:04:02.010 --> 00:04:03.812
And throughout that
time, the clients

00:04:03.812 --> 00:04:06.270
that I would take on the road
for these health and wellness

00:04:06.270 --> 00:04:08.950
vacations wanted
more information.

00:04:08.950 --> 00:04:10.740
How do I implement
this when I get home?

00:04:10.740 --> 00:04:12.087
Traveling with you is fantastic.

00:04:12.087 --> 00:04:13.920
But now I need to figure
out how to put this

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:18.120
into my own lifestyle, which is
how "Living Well on the Road"

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:18.870
came to be.

00:04:18.870 --> 00:04:22.079
It's the book you guys are
all getting a copy of today.

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:24.480
That goes into
health and wellness,

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:26.950
the science behind it,
why these things work,

00:04:26.950 --> 00:04:29.880
which is what we're going
to talk through a little bit

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:30.750
today.

00:04:30.750 --> 00:04:33.210
So one of the things I
think we can all agree on

00:04:33.210 --> 00:04:35.630
is that travel is stressful.

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:36.817
There is no way around that.

00:04:36.817 --> 00:04:38.400
And the first thing
that we have to do

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:41.610
is recognize that
and say to ourselves,

00:04:41.610 --> 00:04:43.320
why is travel stressful?

00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:45.420
Because as humans,
we are hardwired

00:04:45.420 --> 00:04:48.420
to avoid negative experiences.

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:50.030
We've all had a bad
travel experience.

00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:51.030
We've missed the flight.

00:04:51.030 --> 00:04:52.200
We've run for a flight.

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:54.420
We've had an altercation
maybe with the gate

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:57.180
agent who wouldn't get us on
that flight, whatever it is,

00:04:57.180 --> 00:04:57.780
right?

00:04:57.780 --> 00:05:00.240
So those are the
experiences we internalize

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:02.550
and the experiences
that we remember.

00:05:02.550 --> 00:05:04.440
And so we start to
make our decisions

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:07.230
from this fear-based place
of I don't want to do that.

00:05:07.230 --> 00:05:08.680
I don't want to do that.

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:11.550
So let's talk a little
bit about that fear base

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:14.340
and what it is
that it does to us.

00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:17.910
And then let's learn some
tools of how to deal with that

00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:19.330
and move on.

00:05:19.330 --> 00:05:22.920
So when we're talking
about the stress of travel,

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:26.220
the stress of travel affects
our whole mind/body connection--

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:28.860
the physical, the mental,
and the emotional.

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:31.050
When it comes to
our physical selves,

00:05:31.050 --> 00:05:32.730
you can picture
yourself now, right?

00:05:32.730 --> 00:05:34.275
You're running
through the airport.

00:05:34.275 --> 00:05:35.911
You're trying to
make that flight.

00:05:35.911 --> 00:05:37.410
You're the last
person on the plane.

00:05:37.410 --> 00:05:38.785
There's no room
for your luggage.

00:05:38.785 --> 00:05:40.200
So you're trying to cram it in.

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:42.510
You're trying to cram
yourself into the seat, right?

00:05:42.510 --> 00:05:44.580
All of these things are
completely stressful

00:05:44.580 --> 00:05:46.470
and take our body out of whack.

00:05:46.470 --> 00:05:49.740
We're disrupting sleep patterns
when we change time zones,

00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:53.850
even especially if we're doing
it for a short period of time.

00:05:53.850 --> 00:05:56.610
We're increasing our
sedentary behavior.

00:05:56.610 --> 00:05:58.020
You know, you guys
here at Google

00:05:58.020 --> 00:06:00.290
are lucky enough to have
these great outdoor spaces

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:02.790
and these conference rooms so
you can get up and move around

00:06:02.790 --> 00:06:03.540
a little bit.

00:06:03.540 --> 00:06:06.300
That's not the typical workplace
environment these days.

00:06:06.300 --> 00:06:08.730
So people are taking
themselves from sitting

00:06:08.730 --> 00:06:12.510
behind a desk to sitting on a
plane for hours on end, right?

00:06:12.510 --> 00:06:14.340
This is stressing
our physical system.

00:06:14.340 --> 00:06:16.030
When it comes to
our mental system,

00:06:16.030 --> 00:06:17.910
we're also taxing our brains.

00:06:17.910 --> 00:06:20.370
We live in this day and
age, because we're so

00:06:20.370 --> 00:06:22.950
connected all the time
with everything that we do,

00:06:22.950 --> 00:06:26.860
we live in a constant state of
chronic stress on some level.

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:30.540
We have moved away from being
in that nice relaxed place

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:32.610
to being in that place
where we're constantly

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:34.380
in our fight or flight mode.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:37.350
So add on top of that
business travel, right?

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:40.440
You have to make sure
you're working very well.

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:42.540
But then you also have
to make sure, like, oh,

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:44.190
how am I going to pack?

00:06:44.190 --> 00:06:46.360
Am I prepping for my
meetings properly?

00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:48.930
And then the anxiety
and the worry

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:51.390
that's added on
top of that when it

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:53.640
comes to all of these
things, so our brain starts

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:55.380
to work over time.

00:06:55.380 --> 00:07:00.060
And our emotional state, we
have anxiety around travel.

00:07:00.060 --> 00:07:02.220
There is a lot going
on in the world today.

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:03.760
Whether it's where
we're traveling,

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:06.000
whether it's going through
the airport itself,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:07.710
we start to get anxious.

00:07:07.710 --> 00:07:09.030
Am I going to make that flight?

00:07:09.030 --> 00:07:11.010
Have I prepped for that
meeting really well?

00:07:11.010 --> 00:07:14.070
Am I going to have an issue
when I land on the ground?

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:16.590
There's also a lot of
mistrust these days

00:07:16.590 --> 00:07:18.180
in the travel industry.

00:07:18.180 --> 00:07:20.550
I'm sure we've all seen
the viral videos that

00:07:20.550 --> 00:07:22.620
have come out in
the last few weeks,

00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:24.390
even specifically, right?

00:07:24.390 --> 00:07:27.600
So the clients and
everyone who is traveling

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.820
has an inherent mistrust
of these companies

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:33.030
that we are entrusting
our business travel to.

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:35.700
And then fear-- so back
to this making decisions

00:07:35.700 --> 00:07:36.690
from a place of fear.

00:07:36.690 --> 00:07:38.970
Some people are
afraid of flying.

00:07:38.970 --> 00:07:43.410
So that itself sets you
up in a negative space

00:07:43.410 --> 00:07:44.820
before you've even taken off.

00:07:44.820 --> 00:07:46.440
So these are all
things that we have

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:48.810
to deal with when
it comes to travel.

00:07:48.810 --> 00:07:50.340
So why do we do it, right?

00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:52.170
Why do companies
keep sending us out?

00:07:52.170 --> 00:07:56.160
What is the benefit
of business travel?

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:58.740
And there are many benefits
to business travel.

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:00.450
The biggest things
here are it builds

00:08:00.450 --> 00:08:02.490
relationships and retention.

00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:05.940
And that is not only from
the client and employer side,

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:08.940
but also from the employee
to the employer side.

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:11.220
So when you're able
to get on the road

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:13.230
and you meet your
clients face to face,

00:08:13.230 --> 00:08:15.090
it builds these relationships.

00:08:15.090 --> 00:08:18.750
It builds these relationships
between you and your client.

00:08:18.750 --> 00:08:21.840
You bond with your client
when you're in front of them.

00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:24.960
And it endears
you a bit to them.

00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:26.910
You build this
personal relationship.

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:29.520
Also on the other spectrum
of that, employees

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:31.950
who like to travel
or who travel a lot

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:33.929
and have found ways
through these tips

00:08:33.929 --> 00:08:36.840
that we're going to
walk through to make

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:39.270
it a little bit of a leisure
and enjoyable experience

00:08:39.270 --> 00:08:42.450
at the same time, you will
stick with your company longer.

00:08:42.450 --> 00:08:44.700
So that's great for
the company as well.

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:46.170
It increases productivity.

00:08:46.170 --> 00:08:47.850
When you have
face-to-face meetings

00:08:47.850 --> 00:08:50.700
and you're able to
sit-in front of somebody

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:53.550
and talk through problems,
talk through solutions,

00:08:53.550 --> 00:08:56.580
it increases the
project productivity.

00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:59.790
I'm sure all of you, maybe
today, maybe tomorrow,

00:08:59.790 --> 00:09:01.380
will be on a
conference call, right?

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:04.620
So we thought, oh, when
conferencing gets big,

00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:06.000
when video
conferencing gets big,

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.860
we're not going to need that
face-to-face meeting anymore.

00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:11.610
And actually, that
hasn't proved to be true.

00:09:11.610 --> 00:09:13.350
We are more productive
when we have

00:09:13.350 --> 00:09:16.609
our person-to-person,
face-to meetings.

00:09:16.609 --> 00:09:18.150
So when you're on
a conference call--

00:09:18.150 --> 00:09:19.710
I'm sure many of
you have done it--

00:09:19.710 --> 00:09:23.070
the statistics are that 60%
of people on a conference call

00:09:23.070 --> 00:09:25.840
are also doing something
else at the same time.

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:28.350
So they're not really paying
attention to what's going on.

00:09:28.350 --> 00:09:29.995
And some of that's
because maybe you're

00:09:29.995 --> 00:09:31.620
on this big call with
all these people.

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:33.330
And you're not needed
at that moment.

00:09:33.330 --> 00:09:34.620
So you're checking your email.

00:09:34.620 --> 00:09:37.500
You're figuring out what your
dinner plans are going to be,

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:40.680
whatever it is.

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:43.680
And other statistics that have
come out around the conference

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:44.970
call, right?

00:09:44.970 --> 00:09:47.610
And I will tell you
right now, I have never

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:49.894
been one of these
people, that over 50%

00:09:49.894 --> 00:09:51.810
have admitted that while
on a conference call,

00:09:51.810 --> 00:09:53.440
they've been in the bathroom.

00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:55.950
So I'm hoping that they
were on mute, right?

00:09:55.950 --> 00:09:57.520
Because nobody
wants to hear that.

00:09:57.520 --> 00:09:59.490
[LAUGHS] But these
are the things

00:09:59.490 --> 00:10:02.400
that when you have face-to-face
meetings, they don't happen.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:05.040
You don't get distracted.

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:09.130
Getting up, moving, getting out
of your typical environment,

00:10:09.130 --> 00:10:11.100
whether it's a
cubicle or an office,

00:10:11.100 --> 00:10:13.440
promotes out-of-the-box
thinking and creativity.

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:15.240
It puts you in real
life situations

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:17.130
where you're taught
to think on your feet.

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:18.780
And you're taught
to be flexible.

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:20.780
So these are all
things that companies,

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:24.060
in terms of why they want
you to business travel,

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:26.130
makes it productive
and beneficial

00:10:26.130 --> 00:10:28.950
for them as well
as for yourself.

00:10:28.950 --> 00:10:31.590
The statistics around the
spending for business travel

00:10:31.590 --> 00:10:32.270
are huge.

00:10:32.270 --> 00:10:35.790
The global business
travel spend in 2015

00:10:35.790 --> 00:10:38.370
was $1.2 trillion dollars.

